column1: "Sel clear " alert is not genarting in platform_team
column41:
Steps To Reproduce:
 
1)Do force install with master (platform_team_release-20250627_09f15c46)
 
2)Create 3 Node Cluster
 
3)Generate Sel clear alert using "sudo ipmitool -I lanplus -U admin -P Admin@123 -H 10.137.241.122 sel clear"
 
4)After 5 - 7 MIns check whether the sel clear alert is generated or not using "iris_cli alert ls"

01/Jul/25 8:14 PM;araut.thinkpalm;[~apoorv.sarang] Agent installation was failing in automation suite for RHEL 10, So tried manually to see if its working, but it was failing with error.

*Linux agent installation is failing on RHEL 10.0 with error "cp: cannot create regular file '/etc/init.d/cohesity-agent': No such file or directory"*

Could you please let me know on which os and version the agent installation went fine for you ?

*Tried google, And it says /etc/init.d/ folder no longer exists on RHEL 10*

Please check the screenshot

!Screenshot from 2025-07-01 20-14-18.png!;;;
column2080:
02/Jul/25 6:29 AM;abhishek.thakur;We are currently facing three issues.
 * The first issue is related to a missing {{/etc/init.d}} file. Refer [doc|https://docs.google.com/document/d/1H0W7e6n34au6Ivgi7GnWNVtEJggAdUvn20XQB3jPhGQ/edit?usp=sharing] for more details.
 * The second issue concerns a PID-related problem. Specifically, when we start the agent using systemd, we use a configuration file that contains the relevant settings.

{code:java}
ExecStartPre=/bin/mkdir -p /var/run/cohesity-agent
ExecStartPre=/bin/chown -R COHESITY_USER_TEMPLATE:COHESITY_GROUP_TEMPLATE /var/run/cohesity-agent
User=root
Group=root
....
PIDFile=/var/run/cohesity-agent/cohesity-agent.pid {code}
Before starting the {{linux_agent}} script, we create the folder {{/var/run/cohesity-agent/}} and assign ownership of that folder to the user under which the Cohesity agent is installed. However, the {{linux_agent}} script is started by the root user (as mentioned in User), and the PID file is created in the {{/var/run/cohesity-agent/}} folder.

Systemd expects the PID file to be created by the same user that started the script. Since the PID file is created in folder owned by a different user than the one starting the service, systemd fails to track the service properly and reports that the service failed to start — even though the agent may be running in the background.
{code:java}
cohesity-agent.service: New main PID 375330 from PID file does not belong to service, and PID file is not owned by root. Refusing. {code}
Possible fix is to give ownership of this folder to root(Need investigation why it was changed is it fails in certain scenario).

 
 * The third issue concerns installing the RPM agent on RHEL 10, which uses RPM version 4.19 (greater than 4.16). This version enforces stricter signature validation. Since the current package signature does not meet these stricter requirements, the installation fails. We need to update the signing mechanism to comply with the newer RPM version’s signature standards. 

cc: [~mahesh.k] [~rakesh.agrawal] ;;;

26/Jun/25 5:36 AM;piyush.jain;*TLDR:* We are getting this issue because the disk size for disks 16, 23 and 24 (for which the alerts are raised) are way smaller (only ~ 50 GB) compared to rest of the disks in the cluster (which are ~ 1.81 TB). Increasing higher storage disks should solve the issue.

(The point (iv) below points to this.)

{*}Detailed{*}:

i) Yoda logs across different nodes state "No more space available on disk x for ES" for disk 24, disk 23 and disk 16.

[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 logs]\>

{code}
 

ii) From the code, the alert is raised after checking if the ES disk is nearing exhaustion of the reservation quota [(see here)|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/yoda/slave/slave.cc?r=842d1e61ff4266d03d445fe6c9cac62f7fb98969#1028], which is called for every disk [in this loop|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/yoda/slave/slave.cc?r=842d1e61ff4266d03d445fe6c9cac62f7fb98969#1048]. The Yoda slave's [alarm handler periodically checks for the ES Disk Usage|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/yoda/slave/slave.cc?r=842d1e61ff4266d03d445fe6c9cac62f7fb98969#1338] and accordingly triggers the alert if in case it exceeds. There exists a gflag "[yoda_enable_es_disk_usage_check|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/yoda/base/flags.cc?r=6e21eaf990935d5160aefb769cafdd5a11aa0168#888]" which is set true by default. This gflag raises alert if ES disk usage crosses 75% threshold of its reserved disk quota."

 

iii) This alert has been encountered in many FIs in the past ([list here|https://jira.cohesity.com/browse/FI-41997?jql=text%20~%20%22%5C%22ESDiskUsageExceedsThreshold%5C%22%22]). And the general resolution for when this alert is encountered is to increase the disk space reservation. And the steps to do so are captured in [this confluence|https://confluence.cohesity.com/pages/viewpage.action?spaceKey=CKB&title=%5BInternal%5D+CE03008021-ESDiskUsageExceedsThreshold]. The confluence mentions "The default value set for space consumption of the Yoda Search Indices is 1% of the disk size. For some workloads, you have to increase by an additional 1%." So are we running a very heavy workload on the cluster that is causing this issue? 
The confluence mentions the command "du -sh /home/cohesity/data/disks/*/yoda/" to check the ES disk usage. But when I tried to run the command on the cluster, it says "No such file or directory"
{code:java}
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\> du -sh /home/cohesity/data/disks/*/yoda/
du: cannot access '/home/cohesity/data/disks/*/yoda/': No such file or directory
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\> cd /home
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 home]\> ls
support
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 home]\> 
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 home]\> sudo su - cohesity
-bash: sudo: command not found
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 home]\>{code}
This could be because as a "restricted" or support user, the command cannot be run. If such is the case, requesting [~rajasekar.appusamy] to please provide the steps to get un-restricted access to the cluster, so that we can dig further.

 

iv) The "iris_cli disk ls" for disks 16, 23 and 24 show that the disk reservation for yoda is only "1 GB" whereas for other rest of all the services it is always more. See for disk 21 below. And this is because the disk size for disks 16, 23 and 24 is only ~50 GB whereas rest of the disks are around 1.81 TB. And based on the statement mentioned in point 3 above "The default value set for space consumption of the Yoda Search Indices is 1% of the disk size.", yoda should have got roughly 500 MB (1% of 50 GB), but we still got 1 GB.

column2077:
26/Jun/25 2:31 AM;piyush.jain;From the above comment we see that the reason for FATALs for both Yoda and Librarian is "Crashing Yoda/Librarian for testing".  Please ignore the "Client trying to close its session", its not a cause of crash.

From [the yoda code|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/yoda/yoda.cc?r=a3300652e02e8da6d6030824fadc2070ed923441&mo=58517&fi=1497#1497] and [the librarian code|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/librarian/librarian.cc?r=33a71c02cac561d917c35dd5d1579eee423707d5&mo=36350&fi=954#954], we see that the crashing depends on the gflag "yoda_crash_one_in_chance" and "librarian_crash_one_in_chance".

On the cluster, the values of these gflags are updated from default (0) to 120. These values mean that randomly in one of the 120 runs should the Yoda/Librarian services crash.

 
{code:java}
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\> curl 'http://0:25999/flagz' | grep yoda_crash_one_in_chance
  % Total    % Received % Xferd  Average Speed   Time    Time     Time  Current
                                 Dload  Upload   Total   Spent    Left  Speed
100 1135k  100 1135k    0     0   110M      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--  110M
--yoda_crash_one_in_chance=120 [default=0] 
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\> curl 'http://0:26000/flagz' | grep librarian_crash_one_in_chance
  % Total    % Received % Xferd  Average Speed   Time    Time     Time  Current
                                 Dload  Upload   Total   Spent    Left  Speed
  0     0    0     0    0     0      0      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--     0--librarian_crash_one_in_chance=60 [default=0]
100 1111k  100 1111k    0     0   120M      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--  120M
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\>{code}
 

 

This crashing is triggered in the service's alarm handler, [see here for yoda|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/yoda/yoda.cc?r=a3300652e02e8da6d6030824fadc2070ed923441&mo=58517&fi=1497#1476], and [see here for librarian|https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-datainsights_team/librarian/librarian.cc?r=33a71c02cac561d917c35dd5d1579eee423707d5&mo=36350&fi=954#937]. Now, these alarm handlers are invoked at a certain time intervals. The intervals for Yoda and Librarian both are 1 sec (1000 msec). 
{code:java}
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\> curl 'http://0:26000/flagz' | grep librarian_alarm_delay_msecs
  % Total    % Received % Xferd  Average Speed   Time    Time     Time  Current
                                 Dload  Upload   Total   Spent    Left  Speed
  0     0    0     0    0     0      0      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--     0--librarian_alarm_delay_msecs=1000
100 1111k  100 1111k    0     0   154M      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--  154M
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\> curl 'http://0:25999/flagz' | grep yoda_alarm_handler_interval_msecs
  % Total    % Received % Xferd  Average Speed   Time    Time     Time  Current
                                 Dload  Upload   Total   Spent    Left  Speed
100 1135k  100 1135k    0     0   138M      0 --:--:-- --:--:-- --:--:--  138M
--yoda_alarm_handler_interval_msecs=1000
[support@restricted-sv4-mc15-orca-zm181s028763-node-1 ~]\> {code}
 

From the above two gflags, we are asking the cluster to crash once every 2 mins (since alarm handler is invoked 120 times in 2 mins and we are crashing once every 120 times). And the "Crashing Yoda/Librarian for testing" logs above show that the difference between them is about 2 mins on average. 

So this behaviour of constant crashing of Yoda and Librarian is expected given the value of the gflag "yoda_crash_one_in_chance" and "librarian_crash_one_in_chance" that is manually set.

Increasing the value of above gflags should reduce the number of crashes per unit time and hence solve the "FrequentProcessRestarts" alerts. 

cc: [~rajasekar.appusamy] [~shrirang.ballal] [~richa.gautam] ;;;

icebox_exec.st-master-01-cc45190074-node-1.cohesity.log.INFO.20250623-215027.228068.txt:I0623 21:50:33.187394 228263 delete_object_op.cc:104] Starting DeleteObject with object_name: cohesity/ad_3442556414979638_1710912673478_958177654/cloud_chunk_file/238/403/37112045.cfile.0, 
icebox_exec.st-master-01-cc45190074-node-1.cohesity.log.INFO.20250623-215027.228068.txt:E0623 21:50:33.210431 228280 delete_object_op.cc:202] Failed to delete object: cohesity/ad_3442556414979638_1710912673478_958177654/cloud_chunk_file/238/403/37112045.cfile.0 from Azure storage container: system-automation-cav2  with error: kNonExistent
icebox_exec.st-master-01-cc45190074-node-1.cohesity.log.INFO.20250623-215027.228068.txt:E0623 21:50:33.210474 228280 delete_objects_op.cc:98] Failed to delete object with error: 4 and object_name: cohesity/ad_3442556414979638_1710912673478_958177654/cloud_chunk_file/238/403/37112045.cfile.0 {code}
From the logs, its clear that exactly at 21:50:32.165630 - this object has been deleted. But at 21:50:32.992269, 21:50:33.210431 - the DeleteObjectOp is continuously trying to delete the same object and failing with KNonExistent error.

Since we are trying to access the already deleted object, the op is throwing a KNonExistent error.

Now, the question here is why did the ListObjectsOp return the objects that are already deleted.  The reason could be that the objects were soft deleted and when we invoke ListObjectsOp it includes the soft deleted objects as well.
Looking at the traces of DeleteObjectOp, we are not performing a versioned deleted. Hence the objects are still showing up in ListObjectsOp.

icebox_exec.st-master-01-cc45190074-node-1.cohesity.log.INFO.20250623-215027.228068.txt:I0623 21:50:33.187394 228263 delete_object_op.cc:104] Starting DeleteObject with object_name: cohesity/ad_3442556414979638_1710912673478_958177654/cloud_chunk_file/238/403/37112045.cfile.0, 
icebox_exec.st-master-01-cc45190074-node-1.cohesity.log.INFO.20250623-215027.228068.txt:E0623 21:50:33.210431 228280 delete_object_op.cc:202] Failed to delete object: cohesity/ad_3442556414979638_1710912673478_958177654/cloud_chunk_file/238/403/37112045.cfile.0 from Azure storage container: system-automation-cav2  with error: kNonExistent
icebox_exec.st-master-01-cc45190074-node-1.cohesity.log.INFO.20250623-215027.228068.txt:E0623 21:50:33.210474 228280 delete_objects_op.cc:98] Failed to delete object with error: 4 and object_name: cohesity/ad_3442556414979638_1710912673478_958177654/cloud_chunk_file/238/403/37112045.cfile.0 {code}
From the logs, its clear that exactly at 21:50:32.165630 - this object has been deleted. But at 21:50:32.992269, 21:50:33.210431 - the DeleteObjectOp is continuously trying to delete the same object and failing with KNonExistent error.

Since we are trying to access the already deleted object, the op is throwing a KNonExistent error.

Now, the question here is why did the ListObjectsOp return the objects that are already deleted.  The reason could be that the objects were soft deleted and when we invoke ListObjectsOp it includes the soft deleted objects as well.
Looking at the traces of DeleteObjectOp, we are not performing a versioned deleted. Hence the objects are still showing up in ListObjectsOp.

CC : [~kartheek.kolla] [~aiswarya] ;;;

Test steps

# 1. Pre Cleanup
# 2. Generate data
# 3. Unregister and Register sources with DFS  --> {color:#FF0000}*Fails here for Hive*{color}
# 4. Start Backup job
# 5. Yarn poll for backup DFS string
# 6. Poll and verify successful backup job
# 7. Start Recovery job
# 8. Yarn poll for recovery DFS string
# 9. Poll and verify successful recovery
# 10. Post Cleanup, unregister and register with default

Its observed that the api-server pods are in crashloop and restarts due to which the registration of hive source fails.

Commenter Name: Devanshu Singla | Date Commented: Sun Jul 13 22:27:02 UTC 2025 | Comment: RCA for qtrees using NFS3 protocol:
[https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-dataprotect_team/magneto/storage_proxy/ops/create_entity_op.cc?r=9c8c08f3d986abe9c912f56df1d639490356d82f#822] The CreateHardlink function is used to create hardlinks when creating new entity for hardlink files during restore. The function create temp file for 

a. Volume restore in a folder inside the root of volume if tmp_file_path parameter is not provided, and hence volume restore for hardlink in a qtree was failing as it tried to link the hardlink file (in the restored qtree) to tmp file (present in root).

b. FLR creates tmp file inside the restored root directory of the file. eg if folder being restored was /a/b and it contained a file at /a/b/c/d.txt, then tmp file get created at /alternate_or_original_root_directory/b/tmp_file. Hence it will not cause problem as the tmp will be present in the same qtree (except for if folder is being restored at root of another volume. The tmp file will then be present in root and restored hardlink file might be present in a qtree).

Somehow, we are not passing the tmp_file_path attribute or we are not passing it correctly. I haven't been able to test it yet.

[https://gerrit.eng.cohesity.com/c/main/+/66740] introduced restoring hardlinks for qtrees, so I assume volume restore should have been working at that time.
I suspect [https://gerrit.eng.cohesity.com/c/main/+/319912] might have introduced the regression.

column2076:
24/Jun/25 5:39 AM;devanshu.singla;RCA:
Its a day 0 issue which will occur when restoring hardlink present in a tree. In volume restore, when restoring hardlink present in a qtree to original location, we create tmp file, containing data, in the main parent volume and create hardlink pointing to this tmp and later we delete this tmp file. But since the filesystems for qtree and parent volume are different, the hardlink creation fails with STATUS_NOT_SAME_DEVICE error.

Resolution:
For recovery in qtrees, we need to create the tmp folder inside the qtree itself.;;;
column2077:
25/Jun/25 11:37 PM;revathi.balachandran;Steps Tried:
This original location recovery failed after doing some modification like deleting some hardlink and then trying to restore to original location with overwrite.
While trying restore manually by deleting the some random sh file the restore was successfull.
!zapidatarecovered.png|thumbnail! 
While trying to delete the file MIXED-in-MIXED\StaticData\shdir1\008_dir1_shfile and perform restore, the tmp folder is created inside the qtree but data is not available. 
!zapiexactfile .png|thumbnail! 
Job Link [:https://10.14.49.250/recovery/detail/8980967811466216:1749477796249:32023|https://10.14.49.250/recovery/detail/8980967811466216:1749477796249:32023];;;
column2078:
13/Jul/25 3:27 PM;devanshu.singla;RCA for qtrees using NFS3 protocol:
[https://opengrok.corp.cohesity.com/xref/main-dataprotect_team/magneto/storage_proxy/ops/create_entity_op.cc?r=9c8c08f3d986abe9c912f56df1d639490356d82f#822] The CreateHardlink function is used to create hardlinks when creating new entity for hardlink files during restore. The function create temp file for 

a. Volume restore in a folder inside the root of volume if tmp_file_path parameter is not provided, and hence volume restore for hardlink in a qtree was failing as it tried to link the hardlink file (in the restored qtree) to tmp file (present in root).

b. FLR creates tmp file inside the restored root directory of the file. eg if folder being restored was /a/b and it contained a file at /a/b/c/d.txt, then tmp file get created at /alternate_or_original_root_directory/b/tmp_file. Hence it will not cause problem as the tmp will be present in the same qtree (except for if folder is being restored at root of another volume. The tmp file will then be present in root and restored hardlink file might be present in a qtree).

Somehow, we are not passing the tmp_file_path attribute or we are not passing it correctly. I haven't been able to test it yet.

[https://gerrit.eng.cohesity.com/c/main/+/66740] introduced restoring hardlinks for qtrees, so I assume volume restore should have been working at that time.
I suspect [https://gerrit.eng.cohesity.com/c/main/+/319912] might have introduced the regression.;;;

column1072:
Commenter Name: Ayush Agrawal | Date Commented: Fri Jun 27 10:57:07 UTC 2025 | Comment: This is day 0 behaviour and working as expected.

In 7.1.2_u4, single stream log backup is performed which supports db_level progress monitor for only file based jobs. For VDI and volume based jobs, db level pulse are not present, rather the db pulse are present in task pulse logs so no data is missed.

In latest versions, we support multi stream native log backup which has separate db level pulse logs, which was fixed as part of this bug ENG-406775 which was merged as part of multi stream epic.

cc: [~durgesh.kumar.verma]

column1: Automation Update for Teleport Upgrade
column41:

1.  Teleport will run only on rtclient master (the IP address of master can be found from "cluster ls-masters" CLI command)
2. New hidden  parameter "node-ids" added to "support rt enable=true duration-in-hours=120 node-ids=966065266412,966065266408" which when specified will run teleport on these nodes in addition to rtclient master

[~kedar.khedekar] Check why 7.1.2_u4 (which is an older version) is used for 1.33 qualification. 

Kubernetes 1.33 uses containerd for container runtime.

Looks like the container runtime is not able to pull the docker-registry-local.artifactory.eng.cohesity.com/cohesity-datamover:7.1.2_u4 image

docker pull works fine. This could be an intermittent issue with containerd.

In terms of next steps:

We don't yet want to spend any cycles on ibm2_rm. Current goal will be to trigger upgrade train - upgrading from last released build of [7.2.13 to|http://7.2.to/] latest 7.2.14 build. 

This also involves cleaning up the previous cluster, VSI rigel and VSI source instances.

### Testing pytest plugin changes locally
```commandline
# do version update only once
cd pytest_plugins
poetry version patch

# create a build out of changes, build will be available under pytest_plugins/dist/cohesity_pytest_plugins<new_version>.tar.gz
poetry build

# install this local package in your virtaul env
cd ../
source $(poetry env info --path)/bin/activate
poetry add pytest_plugins/dist/cohesity_pytest_plugins<new_version>.tar.gz
{code}
